THE government has called upon the youth, religious and traditional leaders to fully engage in early child development programmes in effort to help build a better generation. The appeal was made here by the deputy Permanent Secretary in the Office of the President (Regional Administration and Local Government), Ramadhan Kailima, noting that developing decent generation is a duty of all people. He said the fight against child violence and other vices affecting children should involve all people, failure of that the nation may head to a wrong direction. The deputy PS argued that traditional leaders if well equipped with knowledge on early child development will help reduce to build good generation. He made the remarks while officiating at the closure of a six-day national training on Early Child Development (ECD). The meeting organized in collaboration with Children in Crossfire, Tanzanian Early Childhood Development Network (TECDEN) and the Union of Tanzanian Press Clubs (UTPC) brought together 79 participants. “It would be important if we start at school levels by establishing clubs and empowering them” he said, adding that those at higher learning institutions can be engaged through social media, among other platforms. Country Director for Tanzania at Children in Crossfire, Mr Craig Ferla said his organisation will champion a partnership with the Tanzanian Early Childhood Development Network (TECDEN) and the Union of Tanzanian Press Clubs (UTPC) to help achieve the government’s goals. Speaking on behalf of the participants, Gaudence Nyamwihura noted that after the training, they will be ambassadors of spreading education to their different plans.